{"cursor":"9819","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"A 'chemical glycosylation' reaction involves the coupling of a glycosyl donor,\nto a glycosyl acceptor forming a glycoside. {{Cite book\n| publisher = Blackwell Publishing isbn = 978-1-85075-913-3 last = Boons first =\n| Geert-Jan coauthors = Karl J. Hale title = Organic synthesis with\n| carbohydrates year = 2000\n}} Crich, D.; Lim, L. [[Org. React.]] '2004', 64, 115.\nBufali, S.; Seeberger, P. [[Org. React.]] '2006', 68, 303.  If\nboth the donor and acceptor are sugars, then the product is an oligosaccharide.\nThe reaction requires activation with a suitable activating reagent. The\nreactions often result in a mixture of products due to the creation of a new\nstereogenic centre at the anomeric position of the glycosyl donor. The formation\nof a glycosidic linkage allows for the synthesis of complex polysaccharides\nwhich may play important roles in biological processes and pathogenesis and\ntherefore having synthetic analogs of these molecules allows for further studies\nwith respect to their biological importance.\n","linknr":259,"url":"Chemical_glycosylation","recorded":1362672335,"links":21,"instances":[],"pdf":[],"categories":["Carbohydrate chemistry","Carbohydrates"],"headings":["Terminology","Stereochemistry","Neighbouring group participation","Protecting groups","Current methods in glycoside synthesis","Notable synthetic products","See also","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5e/MechChemGlycosylation.gif/700px-MechChemGlycosylation.gif","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f5/NGPAcetoxoniumIon.gif/700px-NGPAcetoxoniumIon.gif","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/00/NGPBenzylExample.gif/700px-NGPBenzylExample.gif","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-